SIMPLE: itinerant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Itinerant
<hw>I*tin"er*ant</hw> <pr>(⟦isl⟧*t⟦icr⟧n"⟦etil⟧r*⟦ait⟧nt)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>itinerans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr.
of <ets>itinerare</ets> to make a journey, fr. L. <ets>iter</ets>,
<ets>itineris</ets>, a walk, way, journey. See <er>Errant</er>,
<er>Issue</er>.]</ety> <def>Passing or traveling about a country; going
or preaching on a circuit; wandering; not settled; <as>as, an
<ex>itinerant</ex> preacher; an <ex>itinerant</ex>
peddler.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king's own courts were then <qex>itinerant</qex>, being kept
in the king's palace, and removing with his household in those royal
progresses which he continually made.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Itinerant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Itinerant
<hw>I*tin"er*ant</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>One who travels from place to
place, particularly a preacher; one who is unsettled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Glad to turn <qex>itinerant</qex>,⟦br⟧
To stroll and teach from town to town.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Itinerantly</ent>⟦br⟧
